title: For Sale:  6.5 Rem Mag setup
postcontent: The gun writiers had it right when they wrote that the Remington Guide Rifles and their their three Remington Magnum calibers were ahead of their time.  Like the 10MM that Colt stepped up and built a 1911 for, the Model 673 rifles were offered in just three high performance calibers and in limited numbers.  Look up the ballistics on the 6.5 Rem Mag, and you'll be amazed.  The .300 and .350 hit even harder (and recoil even more), and they were used the world over to take every kind of game effectively, all from a .284 belted short case.  Specs, before the offering of high ballistic coefficient projectiles, too.  Now, here's one that is very little used and more than my old shoulder can handle any more.  And ammo?  Sure, it's rare, but I have ammo... new and once loaded... I have brass, much new, some once loaded... I have reloading dies, and I even have a forming die to make a few other casings into 6.5 Rem Mag.  Again, check the ballistics of this incredible belted magnum from 3450 fps to 2700 fps for 140 grain, again, from a small case.  The ammo and brass alone that I have is worth well over $1000.00, and the rifle is as shown in beautiful shape, jeweled bolt and all.  It's likely you've never seen one of these much less fired one, and this one just sits in the safe, so I need to sell it.  If my shoulder could still stand up to it, I would never even consider selling it.  Please, All, do not waste my time and yours with silliness and fake check/money order offers or other scams.  If you have an interesting trade, maybe a Tavor X95 bluse some cash, let me know, and be honest in your mind about its value as regards this rifle and extras.  Thank you.  Post Script:  Had friends over yesterday and took them to the range.  They loved this rifle, but all three said the recoil was "more than noticeable", and one even got a slight imprint from the scope ocular on his forehead (to brag to his wife?).  They fired about twenty-five rounds before they had to call it quits.  So I can honestly say that it's been recently fired.  If you're headed to Alaska for hunting, surviving or guiding hunters, this is for you.  So, you have a really neat rifle and caliber, and you can add your own caliber work-ups with the new high BC projectiles and powders.  I can consider trades of low recoil rifles such as Tavor.

The design was patented by Georg Luger in 1898 and produced by German arms manufacturer Deutsche Waffen- und Munitionsfabriken (DWM) starting in 1900 with other manufacturers such as W+F Bern, Krieghoff, Simson, Mauser, and Vickers;[3] it was an evolution of the 1893 Hugo Borchardt–designed C-93. The first Parabellum pistol was adopted by the Swiss army in May 1900. In German Army service, it was succeeded and partly replaced by the Walther P38 in caliber 9×19mm Parabellum.

title: For Sale:  AR-15 $0.15/round 223 Rem FMJ Steel Case Russian Ammo
postcontent:
I bought this 223 Rem FMJ Steel Case Russian from SG Ammo in November 2016 at $0.18/round.This ammo is with hard primer, and requires reenforced fire pin or hammer spring -- I will give away them (I paid $25) if you buy the ammo.I have shot 1000 rounds, and only 1 round was not fired with the reenforced fire pin only; no other FTE and FTF issues. I got about 2-4 MOA on a 5x5 group at 100 yard, with my 20" free floating CHF AR (6-24 x 50 scope).I still have 3000 rounds left in the original pack, and I am selling them at $0.15/round OBO.I am a member of Southern Minnesota Sportsman's Club, therefore I can bring you to the shooting range for test shoot or accuracy and cycling check if your prefer.BTW, I have one 1-24 x 4 carbin scope, one Bushnell red dot (box opened, used once), and one Millett red dot (brand new), for fast aimming and fast shooting -- priced for sale.----------------I just received some questions, answer here:This ammo was a pretty hot topic back to October 2016. 
 
From the AR 15 forums, I learned that the original manufacturer was Golden Tiger, made in Vympel Russia, and the steel shell was made of Lacquer steel, which had been specially treated for anti-corrosion; and, the primer and the neck had been sealed -- therefore they are very suitable for long term storage. They were sold at $0.20-0.22 per round at www.SGAmmo.com.

 
However, the whole lot shipped to SG Ammo in October 2016 has a mistake - for some stupid reason, the Russian workers put 5.45x39 primers on the shells. This primer needs deeper firing pin to strike for firing, and somebody also suggested to use a more powerful hammer spring. So the SG Ammo lowered their price to $0.18 per round (started from 2000 rounds pack, shipping included), and stated "sold as is". They suggested to use "enhanced/extended 7.62x39 firing pin", plus "Wolff XP hammer spring". I bought both the firing pin and the hammer spring, but by using this enhanced firing pin, I got only 1/1000 FTF.

 
I am willing to sell the whole 3000 rounds as a whole lot, since I am giving away the firing pin and hammer spring.
 
Thanks.

title: For Sale:  EXC Late 40s Target Sealed 8 Iver Johnson TIGHT! A BEAUTY!
postcontent: This is one of 4 of these cool little revolvers I have had. It is one of the better condition ones I have had and when compared to what is listed. These were sold as target revolvers, a step or two above the "tackle-box" guns made to throw in the truck. Larger checkered grips and a 6 inch barrel make them pretty good shooters. These revolvers had their chambers counter bored or recessed so the cartridge head was enclosed and supported. It also allows the cylinder to mate right up to the frame in the rear. Double action, though for target use, they really shine in single action as the trigger is crisp snd light. This is a second series gun as it has the round barrel and after the WAR they were made from 1946 to 1954. The serial number on this one is most likely very late 1940s. FINISH--The metal has very good bluing as many do not. The frame rates excellent with no real fading or wear and just a few very fine scratches. The triggerguard has some light bluing wear and the metal in front of the grip is like new.The barrel is EXC- as it is just as nice as the frame with light bluing wear at the last 1/2 inch by the muzzle. The cylinder rates Very Good as the bluing is mostly fine but there is very light freckling on just one area which is most likely the area that sat against whatever it was stored in. We are talking very light freckling.The wood rates EXC to EXC+ as the checkering is great with no wear and just the faintest dings and marks from use. The surface finish is 100% intact, so not a spot where it is missing or worn.The trigger and hammer are case-hardened. FUNCTION-- Test fired by me to ensure proper function. With the hammer locked back, the cylinder has just the tiniest movement or play which is truly negligible BUT that is not how you check it....as soon as any pressure touches the trigger, it locks solid with ZERO movement. It has been cleaned and lubricated properly. The bore is perfect. Priced the same as others with damaged chambers and quite a bit of wear. The two mags are the ones originally supplied by Glock and both are the newest “03” version.  One of the mags has a Strike Industries +2 extension floor-plate installed.  I’ve also added a Talon grip to enhance the grip on this slim pistol.  Otherwise, the gun and all mags are bone stock.
I prefer face-to-face transfer in east Texas without shipping.  I’m in College Station so anywhere inside the Houston, Austin, DFW triangle will probably work.  Maybe we can meet halfway to minimize driving. 
Must be a legal buyer, 21 or over with a valid TX driver’s license or permit.
I’d prefer cash, but I can certainly take a look at any trades you may wish to offer.  Mainly I’m interested in a Ruger LC9s Pro, or FDE Glocks, e.g., G-43, G-42 in Glock Dark Earth (not Cerakote).
